    <!-- ===================== SLIDE 18: StreetEasy Floor Plan Fraud ===================== -->
    <section id="s18" data-slide="18" class="py-10 border-b border-war-border/30">
      <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-4">
        <span class="font-mono text-xxs text-war-text-muted">18</span>
        <h3 class="section-title">StreetEasy Listing — Floor Plan Fraud</h3>
      </div>
      <p class="text-sm text-war-text-dim mb-2"><strong>StreetEasy Listing #1279480</strong></p>
      <div class="bg-war-surface2 border-l-2 border-war-amber p-4 rounded-sm mb-4">
        <p class="text-xs text-war-text-dim"><strong>EVIDENCE:</strong> The StreetEasy listing (Listing ID #1279480, URL: streeteasy.com/sale/1279480) displays a two-level floor plan for "13 Harrison Street, Apartment 1." The left panel is labeled "CELLAR" and the right panel is labeled "1st FLOOR."</p>
        <p class="text-xs text-war-text-dim mt-2"><strong>THE FRAUD:</strong> The so-called "Cellar" level shows four distinct areas labeled "SLEEPING AREA" with dimensions (10'-5" × 15'-3"; 12'-0" × 15'-3"; 23'-0" × 15'-0"; and 7'-0" × 14'-0"), plus a "DEN" (23'-0" × 18'-0"). It also shows closets (CL) servicing these rooms — a functional indicator of bedroom use. Two full bathrooms are visible in the cellar layout.</p>
      </div>
      <EvidenceExhibit
        src="documentation-coo/slide-18-streeteasy-floorplan.webp"
        alt="StreetEasy listing floor plan showing cellar labeled with sleeping areas"
        label="StreetEasy #1279480 — Floor Plan"
      />
    </section>

    <!-- ===================== SLIDE 19: StreetEasy Sleeping Area ===================== -->
    <section id="s19" data-slide="19" class="py-10 border-b border-war-border/30">
      <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-4">
        <span class="font-mono text-xxs text-war-text-muted">19</span>
        <h3 class="section-title">StreetEasy — Euphemism Detection</h3>
      </div>
      <div class="bg-war-surface2 border-l-2 border-war-amber p-4 rounded-sm mb-4">
        <p class="text-sm text-war-text font-medium mb-2">"Sleeping Area" as Code Circumvention</p>
        <p class="text-xs text-war-text-dim"><strong>NYC Building Code Definition:</strong> A "bedroom" or "sleeping room" is any room used or intended for sleeping (NYC Admin. Code §28-101.4.3; NYC Housing Maintenance Code). The term "Sleeping Area" is a semantic dodge — there is no legal distinction between a "sleeping area" and a "bedroom" under NYC code. Both require legally complying windows, minimum ceiling heights, and a Certificate of Occupancy designation as habitable space.</p>
      </div>
      <EvidenceExhibit
        src="documentation-coo/slide-19-streeteasy-sleeping-area.webp"
